# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alameda-california
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Oakland City Center/12th Street station opened in 1972 as part of the first section of BART.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] In 1980–1986, the KE Track project added the third track to the station.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] From 1992 to 2002, and 2004 to 2010, it was the timed transfer point between northbound trains.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Tempo bus rapid transit service began in 2020.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station has three underground levels.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The first level is a concourse with ticket machines and faregates.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] An island platform and two main tracks (C1 and CX) for northbound trains (bound for Richmond and Antioch) are on the second level.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] A side platform with one track (C2) for southbound trains (bound for Berryessa or San Francisco) is on the third level.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station has red brickwork, contrasting with the blue of nearby 19th Street Oakland station.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station has eight public entrances: two at 12th Street, three at 13th Street, and two at 14th Street (including one from Frank H.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Ogawa Plaza), plus one from the belowground plaza of Oakland City Center near 13th Street.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Surface elevators are located at the Ogawa Plaza entrance and at the southwest 12th Street entrance, while the platform elevator is at the south end of the station.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] A currently unused passage leads directly to the Central Building at the north end of the station.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Route 1T stops at dedicated platforms at two locations: **14th Street** on Broadway at the north end of the station, and **City Center** just east of Broadway on 12th Street (northbound) and 11th Street (southbound) at the south end of the station.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station, along with 19th Street Oakland and Daly City stations, was designed by Gerard McCue and Associates.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] By 1967, owners of three Oakland buildings were considering paying for private entrances from the station mezzanine.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Only one was actually constructed: an entrance from the Central Building (1400 Broadway) was approved in February 1968.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] By August 1965, the city wanted to called the station "Oakland Downtown South", while BART preferred "Oakland-12".
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] In October 1965, a BART committee recommended "12th Street".
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The BART Board approved **12th Street Oakland** as the name that December.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] In October 1971, after pressure from Oakland officials to include mention of the new Oakland City Center development, the name was changed to **Oakland City Center/12th Street**.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station opened on September 11, 1972, as part of the first section of BART to open; service was extended to Richmond the next year.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Service to Concord was added on May 21, 1973, and extended to San Francisco through the Transbay Tube on September 16, 1974.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Richmond–San Francisco service was added on April 19, 1976.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station was initially built without an elevator between the mezzanine and street level because the city of Oakland refused to allow elevator kiosks on the sidewalks.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] By late 1973, it was the only BART station without an elevator completed or under construction.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] A surface elevator near 11th Street, set back from the sidewalk on a parcel being redevelopment, was ultimately built as part of a $1.47 million modification to the station.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Constructed as part of the City Center development, it also included additional escalators and a new entrance from the City Center plaza.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The United States Department of Transportation awarded $1.17 million for the project in April 1974, and a construction contract was issued that December.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The elevator and new entrance opened along with the plaza and the Clorox Building on October 15, 1976.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] A second elevator was added in Ogawa Plaza in 2002.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station initially had one side platform on each level, with one track on the east side of each platform.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The KE Track project, begun in 1980 and completed on March 17, 1986, converted the upper platform to an island platform with a new west track (Track CX).
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The new track was originally used for peak hour service (southbound towards San Francisco in the morning, and northbound in the evening).
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Schedule changes on June 22, 1992, introduced timed transfers between Richmond–Fremont line and Concord–Daly City line trains.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Oakland City Center/12th Street was the transfer point between northbound (Richmond-bound and Concord-bound) trains, while MacArthur station was the transfer point between southbound trains.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The CX Track became northbound-only at this time.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Timed transfers were discontinued in 2002, but resumed on February 9, 2004.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] The station was renamed to **12th Street Oakland City Center** around 2008.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] On September 13, 2010, the northbound transfer location was changed to 19th Street Oakland station.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Sunday-only service to the station on the Dublin/Pleasanton line was operated from February 11, 2019, to February 10, 2020, due to construction work in the Transbay Tube.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Four of the six entrances were closed from April 13, 2020, to June 12, 2021, due to low ridership during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Construction of the Oakland–San Leandro East Bay Bus Rapid Transit line (later branded *Tempo*) began in August 2016.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Tempo route 1T service began on August 9, 2020, with surface stations at 14th Street and City Center.
[src:alameda-california/12th-street-oakland-city-center-station] Installation of second-generation faregates at the BART station took place in December 2024.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:alameda-california/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:alameda-california/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:alameda-california/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:alameda-california/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] The **1900 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office on June 1, 1900, determined the resident population of the United States to be 76,212,168, an increase of 21.01% from the 62,979,766 persons enumerated during the 1890 census.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] It was the last census to be conducted before the founding of the permanent United States Census Bureau.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] The census saw the nation's largest city, New York City, more than double in size due to the consolidation with Brooklyn, becoming in the process the first U.S. city to record a population growth of over three million — Brooklyn was previously the 4th largest city in the United States on its own.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] Oversight of the statistics was by Frederick Howard Wines and Walter F.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1900 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] Statistician Frederick Ludwig Hoffman criticized the conduct of the census.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1900 census are freely available through IPUMS.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alameda-california/1900-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1900, on a map of the modern United States.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] The **1910 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau on April 15, 1910, determined the resident population of the United States to be 92,228,496, an increase of 21 percent over the 76,212,168 persons enumerated during the 1900 census.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census switched from a portrait page orientation to a landscape orientation.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] This was the last census in which Texas did not record any top 50 largest cities by population, despite being the 5th most populous state at the time.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which all the top 50 largest cities had population over 100,000.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census was the first to use metropolitan districts, the predecessor to modern metropolitan statistical areas, which were defined for all cities with at least 200,000 people.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] Edward Dana Durand, then-head of the Bureau of Corporations, was appointed in 1909 to oversee the census. $14 million were allocated to conduct the census.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1910 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] Number of dwelling house in order of visitation.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] Number of family in order of visitation.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] NAME of each person whose place of abode on April 15, 1910, was in this family.
