[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s; after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along with digital indices.
[src:alameda-california/1910-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1910 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda originally occupied a peninsula connected to Oakland.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The area was low-lying and marshy, while higher ground was part of one of the largest coastal oak forests in the world.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] A local band of the Ohlone tribe inhabited the region for more than 3,000 years.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] They were present at the time of the arrival of the Spanish in the late 18th century.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Ohlone created numerous oyster shell mounds across the peninsula, some as large as 14 feet tall.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Spanish colonists called the area *Encinal*, meaning "forest of evergreen oak".
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] What is now Alameda, and much of the East Bay was included in the vast Rancho San Antonio granted to Don Luis María Peralta by the Spanish king who claimed California.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The grant was later confirmed by the Republic of Mexico after its independence in 1821 from Spain.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Over time, the place became known as Bolsa de Encinal or Encinal de San Antonio.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The city of Alameda was founded on June 6, 1853, following the Mexican–American War of 1848 and the subsequent acquisition of California by the U.S.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The name *Alameda* is Spanish for "grove of poplar trees" or "tree-lined avenue" and was chosen in 1853 as city's official name by popular vote.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The borders of Alameda were expanded to include the entire island in 1872, incorporating Woodstock into Alameda.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The first school, Schermerhorn School, was opened a year later in 1855 (eventually renamed as Lincoln School).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The San Francisco and Alameda Railroad opened the Encinal station in 1864.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The early formation of the Park Street Historic Commercial District (or downtown) was centered near the train lines.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Encinal's own post office opened in 1876, was renamed West End in 1877, and closed in 1891.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] On September 6, 1869, the Alameda Terminal made history; it was the site of the arrival of the first train via the First transcontinental railroad to reach the shores of San Francisco Bay, marking the first coast to coast transcontinental railroad in North America.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Croll Building, on the corner of Webster Street and Central Avenue, was the site of Croll's Gardens and Hotel, used as training quarters for some of the most popular fighters in boxing from 1883 to 1914.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Jack Johnson and several other champions all stayed and trained here.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The need for expanded shipping facilities and increased flow of current through the estuary led to the dredging of a tidal canal through the marshland between Oakland and Alameda.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Construction started in 1874, but it was not completed until 1902, resulting in Alameda becoming an island.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In 1917, a private entertainment park called Neptune Beach was built in the area now known as Crab Cove, which became a major recreation destination in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] It was sometimes referred to as the "Coney Island of the West".
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The popsicle was first sold to the public at Neptune Beach in 1923.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Alameda Works Shipyard was one of the largest and best-equipped shipyards in the country.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Together with other industrial facilities, it became part of the defense industry buildup before and during World War II, which attracted many migrants from other parts of the United States for the high-paying jobs.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In the 1950s, Alameda's industrial and shipbuilding industries thrived along the Alameda Estuary.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In the early 21st century, the Port of Oakland, across the estuary, has become one of the largest ports on the West Coast.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Its operators use shipping technologies originally experimented within Alameda.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] As of April 2006, Alameda is a "Coast Guard City", one of six then designated in the country (as of 2025, it is one of 34).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In addition to the regular trains running to the Alameda Mole, Alameda was also served by local steam commuter lines of the Southern Pacific (initially, the Central Pacific).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda was the site of the Southern Pacific's West Alameda Shops, where all the electric trains were maintained and repaired.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] These were later adapted as the East Bay Electric Lines.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The trains ran to both the Oakland Mole and the Alameda Mole.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In the 1930s Pan American Airways established a seaplane port along with the fill that led to the Alameda Mole, the original home base for the China Clipper flying boat.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In 1929, the University of California established the San Francisco Airdrome located near the current Webster Street tube as a public airport.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Bay Airdrome had its gala christening party in 1930.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Airdrome was closed in 1941 when its air traffic interfered with the newly built Naval Air Station Alameda (NAS Alameda).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In the late 1950s, the Utah Construction Company began a landfill beyond the *Old Sea Wall* and created *South Shore*.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] On February 7, 1973, a USN Vought A-7E Corsair II fighter jet on a routine training mission from Lemoore Naval Air Station suddenly caught fire 28,000 feet (8,500 m) above the San Francisco Bay, crashing into the Tahoe Apartments in Alameda.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Eleven people including the pilot died in the crash and fire.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda has been given the nickname "The Island City".
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda Point, Bay Farm Island, and South Shore are largely built on bay fill.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Not all of Alameda Island is part of the City of Alameda; a small portion of a dump site west of the former runway at Alameda Naval Air Station extends far enough into San Francisco Bay that it is over the county line and therefore part of the City and County of San Francisco.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Ballena Isle, an even smaller island, is also part of Alameda.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda comprises numerous neighborhoods spread across the main island and Bay Farm.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] While the city has no official lists, names have been given to multiple.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] This region experiences warm (but not hot), dry summers, and cool (but not cold), wet winters.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] According to the Köppen climate classification system, Alameda has a warm-summer Mediterranean climate, abbreviated "Csb" on climate maps.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Annual precipitation is about 22 in (560 mm), all rain (snow is extremely rare at sea level in the San Francisco Bay Area).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The low-lying island has seen sea-level and groundwater level rise threaten its infrastructure and people not just through flooding events, but through the increased liquefaction risk from more saturated soils.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The locations of increasing groundwater-induced risks and flooding risks may be most precise in private insurance company maps.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] As of the 2020 census, Alameda had a population of 78,280 and a population density of 7,491.6 inhabitants per square mile (2,892.5/km2).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The census reported that 98.0% of residents lived in households, 0.8% lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 1.2% were institutionalized.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The age distribution was 19.9% under the age of 18, 6.7% aged 18 to 24, 28.4% aged 25 to 44, 27.4% aged 45 to 64, and 17.5% who were 65 years of age or older, and the median age was 41.4 years.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] For every 100 females there were 91.2 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.2 males age 18 and over.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There were 30,980 households in Alameda, of which 30.2% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Of all households, 47.7% were married-couple households, 6.6% were cohabiting couple households, 17.0% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 28.7% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] About 28.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older; the average household size was 2.48.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There were 19,640 families (63.4% of all households).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There were 33,009 housing units at an average density of 3,159.1 units per square mile (1,219.7 units/km2), of which 6.1% were vacant.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.4% and the rental vacancy rate was 5.3%.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Of the 30,980 occupied housing units, 48.3% were owner-occupied and 51.7% were occupied by renters.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In 2023, the US Census Bureau estimated that 25.4% of the population were foreign-born.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Of all people aged 5 or older, 65.4% spoke only English at home, 6.7% spoke Spanish, 6.6% spoke other Indo-European languages, 20.1% spoke Asian or Pacific Islander languages, and 1.2% spoke other languages.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Of those aged 25 or older, 93.4% were high school graduates and 60.3% had a bachelor's degree.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The median household income in 2023 was $132,015, and the per capita income was $72,245.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] About 4.8% of families and 6.9% of the population were below the poverty line.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The 2010 United States census reported that Alameda had a population of 73,812.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The population density was 3,214.9 inhabitants per square mile (1,241.3/km2).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 8,092 persons (11.0%).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Census reported that 72,316 people (98.0% of the population) lived in households, 857 (1.2%) lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 639 (0.9%) were institutionalized.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There were 30,123 households, out of which 9,144 (30.4%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 13,440 (44.6%) were opposite-sex married couples living together, 3,623 (12.0%) had a female householder with no husband present, 1,228 (4.1%) had a male householder with no wife present.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There were 1,681 (5.6%) unmarried opposite-sex partnerships, and 459 (1.5%) same-sex married couples or same-sex partnerships.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] 9,347 households (31.0%) were made up of individuals, and 2,874 (9.5%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There were 18,291 families (60.7% of all households); the average family size was 3.06.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] For every 100 females, there were 91.7 males.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.5 males.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Per capita annual income (in 2013 dollars) in 2009–2013 was $41,340 per the US Census.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Median household income in 2009–2013 was $74,606 per the US Census.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There were 32,351 housing units at an average density of 1,409.0 per square mile (544.0/km2), of which 30,123 were occupied, of which 14,488 (48.1%) were owner-occupied, and 15,635 (51.9%) were occupied by renters.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.1%; the rental vacancy rate was 5.7%.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] 37,042 people (50.2% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units and 35,274 people (47.8%) lived in rental housing units.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There is a large Filipino community; and also a major Portuguese community, from which Tom Hanks' mother came and where Lyndsy Fonseca was raised for some time.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda also has a historic Japanese American community and had a small Japanese business district on a portion of Park Street before World War II, when the city's Japanese population was interned.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] A Japanese Buddhist church is one of the few remaining buildings left of Alameda's pre-war Japanese American community.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Naval Air Station Alameda (NAS), decommissioned in 1997, was turned over to the City of Alameda for civilian development, today known as Alameda Point.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] A cluster of artisan distilleries, wineries, breweries and tasting rooms along Monarch Street at Alameda Point is now referred to by the City of Alameda as "Spirits Alley".
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Admiral Maltings also sits in this area, supplying craft brewers and whisky producers, and is the first craft malting house in California.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Photo-realist Robert Bechtle has painted numerous Alameda subjects, including *Alameda Gran Torino*, which was acquired by the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art in 1974 and remains one of Bechtle's most famous works.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The landmark Alameda Theatre is an Art Deco movie theatre designed by architect Timothy L.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The city restored and expand it to include a theater multiplex.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Altarena Playhouse, which performs comedies, dramas, and musicals, was founded in 1938 and is the longest continuously operating community theater in the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Radium is a planned performing arts complex at the former naval air station and has seasonal shows in an outdoor theater.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The Fourth of July parade is advertised as the longest in the United States.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] It features homemade floats, classic cars, motorized living room furniture, fire-breathing dragons, and marching bands.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] There are multiple major events when streets in Alameda's historic downtown district are closed to vehicular traffic.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Park Street Art and Wine Faire is the biggest and takes place the last weekend of every July with more than 200 artists and vendors.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Seasonal events like the spring and winter markets, as well as themed rum, whiskey and hot cocoa strolls are spread out through the year.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The annual Sand Castle and Sculpture Contest takes place in June at the Robert Crown Memorial State Beach, attracting hundreds of participants.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda Point Antiques Faire is held on the first Sunday of every month at the former Naval Air Station runways.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] It is the largest antiques and collectibles show in Northern California, attracting upwards of 10,000 visitors and featuring 800 dealer booths.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The faire specializes in items 20 years or older, including furniture, decorations, clothing, jewelry, art, pottery, books, and collectibles.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda is a charter city governed by a five-member City Council, including the Mayor, who are all elected at large.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The city operates under a council-manager system defined by the City Charter, with a professional City Manager overseeing daily administration.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The City Manager is responsible for city operations, budget administration, and implementing council policies, distinguishing Alameda from strong-mayor systems often in bigger cities.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The City Attorney and City Clerk report directly to the council.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] As of 2026, Marilyn Ezzy Ashcraft serves as mayor, being elected in 2018 and re-elected in 2022.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The budget for the city is greater than $310 million a year as of the 2023–25 biannual budgets planning cycle.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The City Treasurer and City Auditor are independently elected.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Residents appointed by the Mayor and City Council serve on a range of boards and commissions overseeing major components of the city (for example recreation and parks, library, transportation and planning).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda's government is responsible for a range of municipal services, including public safety, transportation, parks, and land use planning.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Rare to a city of its size, it operates its own city-wide electricity utility, Alameda Municipal Power.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda operates Alameda Free Library, which consists of three branches: the Main Library in downtown Alameda, the Bay Farm Island Library, and the West End Library.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Beyond books, services at the library include events and author talks, computer labs, home delivery of books, as well as e-book, streaming digital media, and audio book catalogs.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Historical resources of Alameda's past include local newspaper and magazine archives, high school yearbooks, books by local authors, and maps.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In 2000 voters authorized a bond measure to construct a new main library to replace the city's Carnegie library, damaged during the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The city also received state funds for the new main library and opened the doors to the new facility in November 2006.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Public primary and secondary education in Alameda is the responsibility of the Alameda Unified School District (AUSD), which is legally separate from the City of Alameda government (as is common throughout California).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] More than 9,000 students are enrolled in the AUSD system across nine elementary, four middle, four high schools.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The California Department of Education School Dashboard reports student performance is "green" and above state standards for English, math and college/career preparation.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The College of Alameda, a two-year community college is part of the Peralta Community College District.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The city has numerous private primary schools, and one private high school, St.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Joseph Notre Dame High School, a Catholic school.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The community is currently served by a non-profit online news outlet called the Alameda Post.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Additionally, a weekly newspaper section of the East Bay Times, the Alameda Journal, is published by the Bay Area News Group, based in Walnut Creek, CA.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda's first newspaper, the *Encinal*, appeared in the 1860s.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Following the *Encinal*, several other papers appeared along geographic lines, and the *Daily Argus* eventually rose to prominence.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Around 1900, the *Daily Argus* began to fade in importance and east and west papers *The Times* and *The Star* combined to take the leading role as the *Alameda Times-Star* in the 1930s.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The *Times-Star* was sold to the Alameda Newspaper Group in the 1970s.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] In 1997, the Hills Newspaper chain was bought by Knight Ridder.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Between 2001 and 2023, the *Alameda Sun* ran a local weekly print newspaper.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda is well connected to the region via road, ferries and nearby rail and air connections.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Vehicle access to Alameda Island is via three bridges from Oakland (Park Street, Fruitvale Avenue, and High Street Bridges), as well as the two one-way Posey and Webster Street Tubes leading into Oakland's Chinatown.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] Alameda and Bay Farm Islands are connected via the Bay Farm Island Bridge, and the Bay Farm Island Bicycle Bridge (the only pedestrian/bicycle-only drawbridge in the United States).
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] California State Route 61 runs down city streets from the Posey and Webster Street Tubes, across the Bay Farm Island Bridge, and south to the Oakland Airport.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The island is just minutes off Interstate 880 in Oakland.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The speed limit for the city is 25 mph (40 km/h) on almost every road.
[src:alameda-california/alameda-california] The city has four active and formal sister city relations as well as inactive ones.
